  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT146-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ tamar varaivoṭu vantu collāṭukiṉṟuḻi (C1+5: niṉṟuḻi) varaivu
          maṟuppavō eṉak kavaṉṟa talaimakaṭkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to HER who was anxious they
          would deny marriage, while they were talking, after HIS relations had come with [an offer
          of] marriage.</p>
      </div>


      <div xml:id="KT146">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> amma vāḻi tōḻi nammūrp</l>
          <l> pirintōrp puṇarppō riruntaṉar kollō</l>
          <l> taṇṭuṭaik kaiyar veṇṭalaic citavalar</l>
          <l> naṉṟunaṉ ṟeṉṉu mākkaḷō</l>
          <l> ṭiṉṟuperi teṉṉu māṅkaṇa tavaiyē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Alas, oh friend, in our village,</l>
          <l>have there [once] been those who united the separated?<note place="foot">puṇarppōr
            iruntaṉar: this construction with a predicative verb of existence following a
            participial noun subject can well be understood literally, namely as a (rhetorical)
            question inquiring about past conditions (the perfective aspect of iruntaṉar), preluded
            by a lamenting amma, and quite obviously expecting a negative answer.</note></l>
          <l>The assembly is a place where they say “today [is] a big [day]”,</l>
          <l rend="indent">with people saying “good, good”,<note place="foot">The problem in this
            poem are the social lacunae: there are no helpful parallels illuminating the notions
            connected with this kind of assembly, and the kiḷavi is dubious, because it is not
            backed up by the wording in any way. Here Tieken's interpretation (a bad outcome of the
            marriage negotiations) is as preposterous as those of his predecessors. The poem simply
            does not allow for conclusions as to Caṅkam marriage customs of the kind that HIS people
            usually come to HER house and propose. And yet, so many Caṅkam cultural notions
            discussed in secondary literature are based on poems just as allusive as this.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">staffs in hand, well-worn clothes on [their] white heads.<note
              place="foot">This line obviously gives a sequence of epithets of honour, the staffs
            and the white hair of old age, the worn cloth (citaval), which has kept, according to
            Srin. and TVG, the same association of honour up to this day. TVG holds it to be used to
            wrap the hair, but it might also simply refer to the clothes they wear.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
